Dialogue: 0,0:00:00.00,0:00:04.20,ReelCaption,,0,0,0,,Frida Kahlo was eighteen when a crash\Nsplit her life in two.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:04.20,0:00:08.90,ReelCaption,,0,0,0,,Before the bus and trolley collided,\Nshe planned on medicine, not mythology.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:08.90,0:00:13.10,ReelCaption,,0,0,0,,The accident shattered her body\Nand forced a long recovery.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:13.10,0:00:18.30,ReelCaption,,0,0,0,,Confined to bed, she faced a mirror\Nand began turning pain into image.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:18.30,0:00:24.00,ReelCaption,,0,0,0,,Her self-portraits did not soften suffering.\NThey made it impossible to look away.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:24.00,0:00:29.70,ReelCaption,,0,0,0,,From a narrow room came a public language\Nof identity, disability, and survival.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:29.70,0:00:34.40,ReelCaption,,0,0,0,,Her body kept arguing with disappearance.\NThe paintings argued back.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:34.40,0:00:40.20,ReelCaption,,0,0,0,,The crash broke the plan.\NThe mirror helped build the work that remains.
